WEBVTT

00:00.002 --> 00:10.354
I should like to call your attention this evening to verses 16 and 17 in the 11th chapter of Paul's Epistle to the Romans.

00:11.034 --> 00:21.186
Two of the verses that we read in the reading just now, verses 16 and 17 in the 11th chapter of Paul's Epistle to the Roman.

00:23.168 --> 00:28.274
Or if the first fruit be holy, the lump is also holy.

00:29.026 --> 00:33.232
And if the root be holy, so are the branches.

00:34.814 --> 00:51.476
And if some of the branches be broken off, and thou being a wild olive tree were at graft in among them, and with them particist of the root and fatness of the olive tree, we must go on to complete burst not against the branches.

00:52.317 --> 00:57.504
But if thou, but if thou burst, thou bearest not the root, but the root thee.

00:57.845 --> 00:58.866
But as I say,

00:58.978 --> 01:04.363
I am anxious tonight to consider, in particular, verses 16 and 17.

01:05.664 --> 01:22.160
Now, here, most of you, I am sure, will recall, we are commencing the consideration of a subsection in the section which runs from verse 11 to verse 32.

01:23.362 --> 01:27.986
You remember, we have divided up the whole chapter into three main divisions.

01:28.258 --> 01:31.884
The first division was from verse 1 to verse 10.

01:32.905 --> 01:51.494
The second division is from verse 11 to verse 32, and then the final section of division verse 33 to the end of the chapter, which is that great doxology at the end of the tremendous argument that the apostle has been working out.

01:51.975 --> 01:54.098
Now, it's very important, obviously,

01:54.498 --> 02:04.112
that when we come to any particular subsection of the division, that we should be clear in our minds as to what the division is about.

02:04.773 --> 02:21.138
So I would remind you, it's essential that we should do so in interpreting these two verses which some commentators don't hesitate to describe as the two most difficult verses in the whole of the Bible, and that is why this instrument is probably not working tonight.

02:21.570 --> 02:25.094
because the devil is anxious that we shouldn't interpret it properly.

02:25.134 --> 02:29.518
Some, I say, regard it as extremely difficult.

02:29.558 --> 02:37.707
Well, therefore, it is more than ever important that we should bear in mind the whole context.

02:37.727 --> 02:45.134
Now, the first division you remember versus one to ten are concerned with establishing that the rejection of Israel is not total.

02:46.616 --> 02:48.658
The apostle proves that in two ways.

02:48.802 --> 02:51.666
by saying that he himself is a believer, though he is a Jew.

02:52.387 --> 03:06.145
And secondly, that there are other Jews also who are believers, there is a remnant according to the election of grace, so that there proves beyond any doubt that the rejection of Israel is not a total one.

03:07.127 --> 03:12.935
Then in the second division, verse 11 to verse 32, his big point is that it isn't final.

03:13.916 --> 03:15.318
It isn't a final rejection.

03:16.079 --> 03:18.482
Now that's the division we are now considering.

03:18.690 --> 03:25.861
And I've suggested that it can be naturally subdivided into a number of subsections.

03:25.881 --> 03:30.428
The first subsection was in verse 11 and 12.

03:31.549 --> 03:37.779
Here in verse 11, he introduces the general theme, have they stumbled that they should fall?

03:38.680 --> 03:40.503
What is it that's happened to Israel?

03:40.523 --> 03:46.552
Is it merely a temporary stumbling, or have they really fallen down finally and completely?

03:47.333 --> 03:48.114
And at once,

03:48.546 --> 03:50.568
He answers by saying, God forbid.

03:52.230 --> 04:00.539
And then leads us into the explanation of why this is only a temporary stumbling and not a final falling.

04:01.060 --> 04:05.244
He says, it is, rather, that through their fall, salvation is come to the Gentiles.

04:05.265 --> 04:08.648
This was one of God's ways of bringing salvation to the Gentiles.

04:09.589 --> 04:14.094
And also, to pervert the Jews themselves to jealousy by so doing.

04:14.114 --> 04:17.458
And then you see, he throws out in verse 12, as we've seen,

04:17.538 --> 04:20.082
this tremendous four view of history.

04:20.843 --> 04:27.774
If the four of them be the riches of the world and the diminishing of them be the riches of the Gentiles, how much more their fullness?

04:28.676 --> 04:31.100
Now that's the theme of the whole division.

04:32.522 --> 04:41.416
But you remember we saw that he has a kind of digression in verses 13, 14 and 15.

04:42.959 --> 04:45.042
He now is speaking personally

04:45.122 --> 04:49.127
And he wants the Gentiles to know why he's making so much of this point.

04:50.489 --> 04:55.616
And his answer is that he's doing so because of his concern for the Gentiles.

04:55.636 --> 04:58.760
He is the apostle to the Gentiles, and he magnifies his obvious.

04:59.601 --> 05:05.088
He wants them to have a full understanding and enjoyment of their great salvation.

05:05.108 --> 05:05.990
He puts that like this.

05:07.251 --> 05:10.355
I speak to you Gentiles in as much as I am the apostle of the Gentiles.

05:10.496 --> 05:12.338
I magnify my nothius.

05:12.482 --> 05:18.688
If by any means I may provoke to emulation them which are my flesh and might save some of them."

05:18.708 --> 05:19.689
That's what he's doing.

05:19.749 --> 05:28.638
He's mainly the apostle to the Gentiles, but he does hope that at the same time some Jews will see the truth through his preaching and will be added to the church.

05:28.658 --> 05:33.082
He doesn't expect many at this stage, but he does hope that some will come.

05:33.782 --> 05:41.650
But he says, and here you see he returns to his big theme thrown out in verse 12, if the casting away of them

05:41.730 --> 05:47.357
be the reconciling of the world, what shall the receiving of them be but life from the dead?

05:47.637 --> 05:52.423
Now that's where we ended when we last met on Friday, December the 11th.

05:53.043 --> 06:05.759
He says that a day is coming that when the nation of Israel as a whole, as it were, doesn't mean every single individual, that the nation in bulk are going to see the truth and believe it.

06:05.859 --> 06:08.722
And when that happens, it's going to be

06:09.218 --> 06:17.007
A time of unusual refreshment for the whole Church of God, and especially therefore for the Gentiles.

06:17.387 --> 06:19.409
It will be a most thrilling period.

06:20.050 --> 06:26.998
The nearest we can come to imagining in that is to read of what happens in times of revival.

06:27.018 --> 06:31.563
But when this great event will take place, it will eclipse every revival that's ever been.

06:31.944 --> 06:34.066
It will be rarely like life from the dead.

06:34.402 --> 06:43.055
There's no other comparison that the Apostle can think of that he's adequate to convey any kind of impression of what a glorious time it is going to be.

06:43.556 --> 06:49.185
Now then, we come now to this further subsection.

06:51.368 --> 07:00.242
And here he tells us that something further is necessary still, to be told.

07:02.210 --> 07:15.086
The danger is that the Gentiles should misunderstand their whole position with respect to the church and to the Jews and to the whole question of salvation.

07:15.106 --> 07:19.271
And the apostle wants to safeguard them against them.

07:19.291 --> 07:25.078
So in this subsection, he takes up this matter.

07:25.098 --> 07:28.082
And that is why it is such an important statement.

07:28.962 --> 07:47.448
It is perhaps the most important statement anywhere in the Bible of the respective positions of Jews and Gentiles in the Christian Church and their relationship to one another and their relationship together to the whole of the Church.

07:48.549 --> 07:54.658
Now then, here again is something that I want to subdivide.

07:54.978 --> 07:57.522
In other words, we've got to subdivide what he says

07:57.698 --> 08:01.063
from verse 16 to verse 32.

08:02.966 --> 08:11.599
But I'm only concerned for the moment with the subsection that runs from verse 16 to verse 22.

08:12.640 --> 08:16.246
That's the first division, 16 to 22.

08:19.611 --> 08:21.253
Now, how do we analyze this?

08:21.774 --> 08:24.638
Well, I suggest an analysis along these lines.

08:25.499 --> 08:27.282
In verse 16 and 17,

08:28.130 --> 08:38.021
He states the fundamental relationship of Jew and Gentile in the Church.

08:38.041 --> 08:51.415
In verses 18 to 21, he issues a serious pastoral warning to the Gentiles not to misunderstand this relationship and not to give way to pride.

08:53.237 --> 08:57.522
And thirdly, in verse 22 itself,

08:57.986 --> 09:04.976
He sums up the whole of this particular argument in terms of a general proposition.

09:05.197 --> 09:19.017
Behold, therefore, the goodness and severity of God, on them which fell severity, but toward the goodness, if they will continue in his goodness, otherwise they also shall be cut off.

09:19.037 --> 09:25.266
Now, then, there is a kind of analysis of this immediate posture.

09:27.426 --> 09:31.310
Now this is a tremendously important matter, I say, for this reason.

09:32.532 --> 09:34.914
The apostle here does quite a number of things.

09:36.596 --> 09:48.910
The main thing, of course, is to bring out his third argument with respect to the position of the Gentiles as regards salvation in the Christian church.

09:49.411 --> 09:54.096
You remember his first argument was that he himself is a believer and in the church.

09:54.116 --> 09:56.018
But secondly, there is this

09:57.058 --> 09:59.180
remnant according to the election of grace.

09:59.801 --> 10:03.085
But now here comes a third great argument.

10:04.466 --> 10:26.290
And in developing this argument, he gives us this extraordinary insight, not only into God's plan and purpose, back into the whole question of the nature of the church and the respective places and positions of the Jews and the Gentiles in the church.

10:28.098 --> 10:30.320
And what he rarely is going to tell us is this.

10:32.383 --> 10:44.076
That the Jews, speaking nationally, have a special place in this whole purpose of God with respect to the Church.

10:44.876 --> 10:47.059
Now, I put it like that in general.

10:47.339 --> 10:55.748
As we go on with the interpretation, we will see that there are dangers and errors that we have to avoid on many sides.

10:55.989 --> 10:57.330
But there it is in general.

10:57.986 --> 11:06.099
He is concerned to say, this is his argument in the entire chapter, that far from the Jews being finished with or cast out finally.

11:07.501 --> 11:12.289
They are still in the purpose of God, in a national sense.

11:13.511 --> 11:17.517
But we've got to be very clear as to how that is to be worked out.

11:18.699 --> 11:25.490
And he will show us this special place of the Jews, particularly in its relationship to the place

11:25.602 --> 11:29.706
and the position that is occupied by the Gentiles.

11:31.028 --> 11:35.473
Now then, let's try to proceed to consider the interpretation of this.

11:35.733 --> 11:45.624
Let's take our usual pass and start first of all with a pure analysis of the statement.

11:45.644 --> 11:49.829
You notice that he starts with the word for.

11:49.849 --> 11:54.834
Here is his connecting link, but rarely this shouldn't be translated

11:55.042 --> 12:02.189
as for the better translation here is but, or now, or since.

12:03.810 --> 12:10.757
Now then, since then, but, because, take it like that.

12:12.359 --> 12:13.960
He's going to put an argument before us.

12:14.961 --> 12:16.883
It's connected with what has been going before.

12:18.424 --> 12:24.370
He, you see, has already thrown at this great idea that a fullness

12:24.738 --> 12:27.202
of the Jews is going to come in.

12:28.864 --> 12:33.991
And he's now going to tell us why that must of necessity be the case.

12:34.813 --> 12:35.954
That's what he's setting out to prove.

12:36.635 --> 12:43.505
And here he says, well, now that this is so, and they're coming in will be like life from the dead from the whole church.

12:44.787 --> 12:45.007
Why?

12:45.148 --> 12:48.913
Well, because he says, and then he gives us two pictures.

12:50.676 --> 12:52.338
The first picture is this.

12:53.346 --> 12:59.094
If the first fruit be holy, the lump is also holy.

13:00.256 --> 13:05.603
The second picture is, if the root be holy, so are the branches.

13:07.025 --> 13:15.697
Now, these pictures have caused the great deal of trouble to many commentators and to many people who have studied this picture.

13:16.078 --> 13:19.122
So it's important that we should try to be clear about them.

13:20.002 --> 13:25.629
The difficulty is generally a reason because people, the moment they see this word, first fruit, go off at a tangent.

13:27.071 --> 13:31.457
What they tend to do, of course, is to get hold of a concordance and look up.

13:32.098 --> 13:36.624
The reference is the first fruit and then they jump at once to various conclusions.

13:37.585 --> 13:44.094
They find that the Lord Jesus Christ is referred to as the first fruit of them that are risen from the dead.

13:45.095 --> 13:47.378
And that sends them off along that line.

13:47.746 --> 13:58.040
Then they remember that at the time of harvest, in the ancient days of the children of Israel, they would always gather the first fruit of the harvest and make a meal of it.

13:58.520 --> 14:02.706
Or they would take an offering and wave it before God.

14:02.926 --> 14:06.070
The first fruit of the harvest was offered to God.

14:06.491 --> 14:14.962
And they've tended, therefore, to have their exposition controlled almost exclusively by this idea of the first

14:16.610 --> 14:30.327
But now many others point out and it seems to me quite rightly that that is quite a mistake because the apostle is thinking about first fruit here in terms of a lump.

14:30.347 --> 14:35.913
And you don't speak of a lump of grain or a lump of fruit.

14:35.933 --> 14:46.546
And that surely ought to put us right on this subject, that we are not dealing as it were with a number of sheaves of corn or of something like that gathered and offered up to God

14:47.298 --> 14:51.684
but we are dealing with a first fruit of a lump.

14:51.704 --> 14:58.794
And there is, of course, in the Old Testament an exact description of the very thing to which the apostle is referring.

14:59.175 --> 15:05.784
You will find it in the book of Numbers in chapter 15 and verses 19 to 21.

15:06.085 --> 15:10.411
And there is undoubtedly the thing to which the apostle is referring.

15:10.451 --> 15:12.594
Let me read these verses to you.

15:14.274 --> 15:30.129
Let me start at verse 17, the Lord speak unto Moses, saying, speak unto the children of Israel, and say unto them, when ye come into the land, whether I bring you, then it shall be that when ye eat of the bread of the land, ye shall offer up and heave offering unto the Lord.

15:30.650 --> 15:38.497
Now, then here's the particular thing, ye shall offer up a cake of the first of your dough for an heave offering.

15:39.879 --> 15:43.282
As ye do the heave offering of the threshing floor,

15:43.426 --> 15:47.631
So shall he heave it of the first of your dew.

15:48.752 --> 15:53.378
He shall give unto the Lord and heave offering in your generations.

15:53.939 --> 15:56.622
So that what we must think of is a lump of dew.

15:58.945 --> 16:07.815
Corn is now being ground and the meal has been mixed and it's all there as a mass or a great lump of dew.

16:07.996 --> 16:13.362
Now there to take a bit of that and to bake it into a cake and to offer that

16:13.666 --> 16:15.008
to God.

16:15.028 --> 16:39.057
And the teaching was that the offering of that first bit out of the lump of a mess of the dough, the offering of that to God as a holy sacrifice, the setting apart of that or the consecrating, if you like, of that to God means that the remainder of the lump also becomes holy.

16:40.259 --> 16:42.962
If the specimen is holy, the whole mess

16:43.042 --> 16:43.623
is holy.

16:43.903 --> 16:44.784
That was the teaching.

16:45.184 --> 16:53.293
Under the Old Testament dispensation, it was God's own teaching to the children of Israel, and the apostle here takes it up and uses it as an illustration.

16:54.134 --> 16:59.279
But then he comes to the second illustration, which is a much more direct and straightforward one.

16:59.599 --> 17:01.181
He says, if the root be holy.

17:02.462 --> 17:05.425
So also are the branches.

17:07.227 --> 17:09.069
Now, there's no difficulty here what he's saying.

17:09.129 --> 17:09.970
Here is this.

17:10.210 --> 17:20.705
that there is this essential, intimate, organic relationship between the root and the branches, so that what is true of the roots must of necessity be true of the branches.

17:21.246 --> 17:25.753
Whatever root you plant in the ground, well, you will know exactly what you expect to come up.

17:26.474 --> 17:29.919
The nature of the root and the branches is one.

17:30.860 --> 17:34.966
And so he argues that if the root is holy, the branch is also in the spay holy.

17:36.489 --> 17:40.114
Now, the word holy is a bit important here, obviously.

17:41.186 --> 17:44.792
and there is really no trouble about its interpretation.

17:45.613 --> 17:55.569
As long as we realize that it doesn't refer so much to moral character as to something which has been consecrated or dedicated to God.

17:56.871 --> 17:59.194
You mustn't bring in the notion of perfection.

18:01.218 --> 18:04.162
Sometimes the word holy does carry that meaning.

18:04.282 --> 18:09.170
When we read that God is holy, it means he's absolutely perfect and seamless.

18:09.762 --> 18:11.805
But the word holy doesn't always mean that.

18:12.867 --> 18:14.710
And we must always bear that in mind.

18:16.012 --> 18:23.905
The word holy in its primary meaning carries this idea and this notion of something that is set apart for God.

18:23.925 --> 18:30.897
So you'll get the mount on which the Ten Commandments were given to Moses being referred to as the holy mount.

18:31.779 --> 18:36.306
It was a holy mount because God had told them to set it apart and to

18:36.450 --> 18:40.194
They remember there to put up fences and the people were not allowed to approach it.

18:40.214 --> 18:44.959
You read about the vessels in the temple and they're called holy vessels.

18:45.760 --> 18:55.470
It doesn't mean that there is some unusual purity about them more than any others, but that they've been set apart for this peculiar service of God.

18:56.011 --> 19:02.898
Or if you want a still better illustration of the use of this word holy, you get it of course.

19:03.074 --> 19:17.917
in that statement in 1 Corinthians 7, where the apostle is dealing with the position of a wife who's a Christian who's got an unconverted husband and the whole question of the children.

19:18.257 --> 19:30.155
You get it there in verses 14 and following, for if the unbelieving husband is sanctified by the wife and the unbelieving wife is sanctified by the husband, else where your children unclean.

19:30.456 --> 19:32.018
But now are they holy?

19:32.962 --> 19:37.527
When it says that they're holy, it doesn't mean that they're sinless and that they're perfect.

19:37.807 --> 19:41.571
All it means is that they're allowed to belong to the church.

19:41.671 --> 19:44.334
They come as it were into the realm of the church.

19:44.755 --> 19:46.116
It doesn't mean moral purity.

19:46.857 --> 19:52.323
It means that they are amongst God's people, and it means no more than that.

19:53.104 --> 19:57.188
Very well, because the same thing is said about the unbelieving problem.

19:57.208 --> 19:58.930
Well, now there are the terms.

20:00.770 --> 20:02.632
So the apostle is arguing like this.

20:02.672 --> 20:15.464
He says, if that first bit of dough is consecrated and dedicated to God in that way, well, then God has said that he will regard the whole lump in the same light.

20:16.485 --> 20:22.692
And as I say, the second picture is that the root determines the nature of the tree and the branches.

20:25.955 --> 20:29.298
The question that arises for our interpretation, this is

20:29.378 --> 20:36.124
where you've had a variety of opinions, is how do we now regard these two pictures?

20:37.826 --> 20:43.231
It seems to me to be quite clear that they rarely are both saying exactly the same thing.

20:44.813 --> 20:48.676
Why then do you say that the apostle used two illustrations?

20:48.696 --> 20:51.679
The answer to that is that this is something which is done quite commonly.

20:52.260 --> 20:58.866
He remembered that teaching in the Old Testament, but he thinks of this second illustration

20:59.330 --> 21:11.087
which helps him to work out the point he's anxious to explain more fully than does the one of the portion of this lump of dough which has been consecrated to God.

21:12.129 --> 21:16.856
So he gives the first illustration, he adds a second and it's the second that he takes up and works out.

21:17.176 --> 21:27.031
But the majority of commentators are agreeing that we must interpret the two pictures as conveying the same essential teaching.

21:27.952 --> 21:29.234
So the question before us

21:29.410 --> 21:30.411
really comes to this.

21:31.753 --> 21:35.697
Two whom does the term first fruits refer?

21:36.698 --> 21:39.581
Two whom does the word root refer?

21:40.723 --> 21:44.587
The first fruit is to the lump, exactly what the root is to the branches.

21:45.468 --> 21:48.571
So the question is, what's the meaning of the first fruit and the root?

21:50.313 --> 21:58.002
Now here there are two main expositions which have been put forward.

21:58.818 --> 21:59.899
There is a third.

21:59.919 --> 22:04.184
I think it's most unusual and most uncommon.

22:04.664 --> 22:12.052
I merely mention it because I actually find it in the works of B.W.

22:12.072 --> 22:20.140
Newton, one of the well-known and famous writers amongst the Plymouth brethren during the last century.

22:21.121 --> 22:25.906
He takes the astonishing view that the first fruit referred to here

22:26.466 --> 22:29.430
means Christians, even ourselves included.

22:30.491 --> 22:39.382
All those who belong to the Christian church before this great day that is going to come, that is referred to in verse 15.

22:39.923 --> 22:50.175
Now, that I really feel is an idea that can only have arisen in his mind because he was governed solely, as I say, by this word, first fruits.

22:51.637 --> 22:55.762
And therefore he argues, you see, everything before the actual harvest is first fruits.

22:56.194 --> 23:01.880
So all believers up until the day when Israel as a nation believes, he regards his first speech.

23:03.682 --> 23:08.487
I really can see nothing whatsoever in favor of such an exposition.

23:08.647 --> 23:14.414
So we can content ourselves with concentrating upon the other two ideas.

23:15.415 --> 23:25.746
Now, quite a common interpretation of this matter is this, that the first fruits is a reference to the

23:25.826 --> 23:27.828
first Jewish converts.

23:29.631 --> 23:32.474
I mean by that people like the Apostle Paul himself.

23:34.336 --> 23:38.381
The first believers were, after all, says this argument, Jews.

23:40.403 --> 23:42.446
And therefore they are the first root.

23:43.867 --> 23:49.394
And what the Apostle is saying here is this, that as the first believers of the Gospel were Jews,

23:50.786 --> 23:54.711
start in Jerusalem, then go to Samaria, then to the autonomous parts of the earth.

23:55.092 --> 23:59.998
And they quote our log statement to the woman of Samaria, salvation is on the Jew.

24:01.340 --> 24:16.260
So they argue that the first root is a reference to the first Jewish Christians and that the apostle is arguing that as the first believers were Jews, so the great harvest is going to be that of Jews also.

24:17.322 --> 24:20.626
Now, this is quite a popular

24:21.858 --> 24:24.661
interpretation, especially at the present time.

24:25.902 --> 24:37.835
I was interested to notice that Professor F. F. Bruce, in his Tyndale commentary issued in the last few years, tends to take this point of view.

24:37.895 --> 24:38.756
He puts it like this.

24:38.816 --> 24:42.219
He says, here, but you notice he's careful, he's not quite happy about it.

24:42.880 --> 24:48.786
Here, the first fruit most probably comprises those people of Jewish birth

24:48.962 --> 24:54.030
who had liked Paul, accepted Jesus as Messiah and Lord.

24:54.972 --> 24:57.536
But as he goes on, he isn't quite as happy about it.

24:58.578 --> 25:02.063
He goes on to see if the root be holy, so the branch is changing the metaphor.

25:02.464 --> 25:08.614
Paul now says that since the whole of the trees of one character throughout, the holiness of the root sanctifies the branches.

25:09.616 --> 25:13.282
It is natural to give the root the same significance as the first root.

25:13.302 --> 25:15.986
But if the root and branch figure stood by itself,

25:16.930 --> 25:23.938
We should think of the patriarchs as constituting the root of the tree whose branches are the Israelites of the Christian era.

25:24.578 --> 25:31.045
This would be in line with Paul's later description of Israel as beloved for the Father's sake, verse 28.

25:31.686 --> 25:40.175
Perhaps there is a transition of thought here as Paul passes from one metaphor to the other, and then he had still another further thought because he's got a footnote.

25:40.575 --> 25:46.802
It is, of course, possible to interpret the first fruit of verse 16 of the patriarchs.

25:47.330 --> 25:49.994
but this is a less likely interpretation.

25:50.615 --> 25:56.124
Now, I quote that to you in order to show that he clearly finds it difficult.

25:56.144 --> 26:01.853
He doesn't give us his reasons, but he just says that it is a less likely interpretation.

26:02.313 --> 26:06.780
Well, I want to suggest to you that it is not less likely, but much more likely.

26:07.642 --> 26:15.474
And indeed, the only one that seems to me to be harmonious with the whole argument, as he finds himself saying,

26:16.834 --> 26:24.285
The more you think of it in terms of root and branches, the more you are compelled to adopt another explanation rather than this.

26:24.305 --> 26:28.472
But it seems to me that the argument which should be final at this point is this.

26:30.976 --> 26:45.778
If you say that the first root and the root means believing Jews like the Apostle Paul and others, well then you must say

26:46.978 --> 27:01.920
that the branches, namely the Jews at present and converted, but who are later to be converted correspond to the branches that come out of this particular root.

27:02.341 --> 27:16.402
In other words, you are saying that the unconverted Jews are the branches which come out of the Jews converted at the time

27:16.514 --> 27:18.417
of the Apostle Paul and others.

27:18.797 --> 27:28.591
Now that seems to me entirely wrong for this reason, that the whole argument of the entire chapter is to say this, that the whole bulk of the nation is outside, it is temporary rejected.

27:28.852 --> 27:33.398
He'll say this, this temporary blindness, there is no connection there.

27:33.418 --> 27:41.189
So we cannot say that he's arguing that these are branches that come out of that particular root.

27:42.471 --> 27:44.594
It is inconceivable that he should say so.

27:46.082 --> 27:46.743
very well then.

27:46.823 --> 27:48.125
What is the exposition?

27:48.185 --> 27:51.429
Well, I take the one that has already been quoted to you.

27:52.350 --> 28:06.528
The only natural interpretation here surely, especially as we bear in mind the apostle's whole fundamental objective, is to say that the first fruit consists of the patriarchs.

28:06.548 --> 28:11.634
I mean by that Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in particular.

28:11.810 --> 28:12.090
Why?

28:12.411 --> 28:18.360
Well, because they were the beginning of the Jewish nation.

28:18.380 --> 28:21.665
They are the root of the Jewish nation.

28:21.685 --> 28:28.195
They are this first root, the lump, the first portion of the great nation that came.

28:28.375 --> 28:30.919
There was a point when it was just Abraham alone.

28:30.939 --> 28:40.754
But then come Isaac and Jacob, and you get these constant references, therefore in the scripture to the God of Abraham, Isaac,

28:40.866 --> 28:41.767
end of Jacob.

28:43.088 --> 28:45.531
There you have your first root.

28:47.373 --> 28:54.380
Now, you notice that when he comes to talk about the other picture, it is in the singular.

28:54.480 --> 28:59.826
If the root be holy, he argues, so are the branches.

29:00.847 --> 29:07.794
And here, I don't hesitate to assert, is a reference to Abraham himself, Abraham Al-Hul.

29:08.770 --> 29:12.935
Abraham, after all, is the root of the Jewish nation.

29:12.955 --> 29:22.127
Now, my argument is, you see this, that the apostle is concerned in the whole of this chapter with the Jews as a nation, the Jews as a whole.

29:23.909 --> 29:30.577
And he is going to substantiate this statement of his that a day is coming when, as a bulk, they will come in.

29:30.897 --> 29:37.906
Now, this is his argument, the beginning, the first cake that was offered with the big girl, that was holy, the root

29:38.594 --> 29:41.238
which is Abraham himself was holy.

29:41.498 --> 29:47.266
Therefore, what comes out of Abraham belongs to the same general and essential category.

29:47.286 --> 29:50.431
Now, my justification for arguing like this is this.

29:50.851 --> 29:57.821
We've already found him in the fourth chapter of this great epistle referring to Abraham in this very sense.

29:58.682 --> 29:59.704
What shall we say then?

30:00.165 --> 30:00.926
Says verse 1.

30:01.647 --> 30:06.834
What shall we say then that Abraham, our father, as pertaining to the flesh has found?

30:07.778 --> 30:12.204
Abraham is the father of the Jewish nation.

30:13.245 --> 30:16.930
He is the root out of which they have all come.

30:17.591 --> 30:21.516
They were very proud of this and the apostle is reminding them of it.

30:22.777 --> 30:29.666
Now you recall that the prophets of the Old Testament often gives this precise argument.

30:29.686 --> 30:35.954
Let me give you one in the prophet Isaiah in chapter 51 verses 1 and 2.

30:37.186 --> 30:59.753
talking to me, ye that follow after righteousness, ye that seek the Lord, look unto the rock when he are human and to the whole of the pit when he are dead, look unto Abraham your father and unto Sarah that bear you, for I called him alone and blessed him and increased him."

31:00.755 --> 31:01.135
That's it.

31:01.395 --> 31:02.397
Abraham is the father.

31:02.717 --> 31:06.962
He's the pit out of which this rock has been human.

31:07.874 --> 31:15.625
And, of course, you get the Apostle Paul using exactly the same argument in the third chapter of the Epistle to the Galatians.

31:16.106 --> 31:18.229
Look at verses 14 to 60.

31:20.372 --> 31:23.817
He says that Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law.

31:24.178 --> 31:24.438
Why?

31:24.759 --> 31:30.066
Well, that the blessing of Abraham might come on the Gentiles through Jesus Christ.

31:31.008 --> 31:35.314
That we might receive the promise of the Spirit through faith.

31:36.578 --> 31:38.581
Rather than I speak after the men are of men.

31:39.522 --> 31:45.190
Though it be but a men's covenant, yet if it be confirmed, no men dishonoreth or adhere to.

31:45.491 --> 31:49.517
Now to Abraham and his seed, where the promise is made.

31:50.678 --> 32:04.498
And especially at the end of this chapter, in verses 28 and 29, there is neither Jew nor Greek, there is neither bond nor free, there is neither male nor female,

32:04.994 --> 32:19.936
For you are all one in Christ Jesus, and if ye be Christ's, then are ye Abraham's seed and heirs according to the promise?"

32:19.957 --> 32:34.258
Very well then, that I say should drive us to the inevitable conclusion, that the root out to which the branches come is none other than Abraham.

32:34.978 --> 32:45.973
He is the beginning, even as the patriarchs in general are the first root of this mess, this lump of dough.

32:47.435 --> 32:49.779
Now, there is a pure bit of exposition.

32:49.859 --> 32:51.421
What did all leaders do?

32:54.906 --> 33:03.858
I argue that before we can arrive at a definite conclusion, we've got to consider the statement of verse 17, because it helps us

33:03.970 --> 33:05.533
to understand verse 16.

33:08.237 --> 33:29.874
If some of the branches be broken off, and there were wild olive trees, were at grafting among them, and with them partigists of the root and the fatness of the olive tree, now we needn't follow the argument for the moment, all we need consider is this, that he tells us that some of the branches have been broken off.

33:31.170 --> 33:44.884
and that others from a wild olive tree have been graphed in, and that they begin to partake of the root and the fatness of the olive tree.

33:45.385 --> 33:55.796
Now, here is a tremendous statement, and this is the point at which some of the commentary to say that we are dealing with the most difficult matter in the whole of the scripture.

33:55.816 --> 33:57.938
This whole question of the olive tree

33:58.946 --> 33:59.947
What is the picture?

34:00.068 --> 34:06.517
What exactly is the apostle saying leading up to the question of what then is the olive tree that he's talking about?

34:07.319 --> 34:12.186
And this is again where you get your variety of interpretations and expositions.

34:14.589 --> 34:17.774
Now the apostle puts a picture before us.

34:17.794 --> 34:23.523
He says, here is a good olive tree, here's a wild one.

34:23.543 --> 34:28.370
Because some of the branches of the good olive tree are not bearing fruit, they're cut off.

34:28.706 --> 34:29.347
thrown away.

34:30.809 --> 34:38.401
And some branches are taken from that wild olive tree and they're graphed into this good olive tree.

34:39.483 --> 34:48.718
The meaning of the phrase graphed in among them really is graphed in in their place, graphed in instead of them.

34:48.738 --> 34:53.665
We don't say graphed today, we say graphed, but that of course doesn't make any difference.

34:53.706 --> 34:56.530
That's simply the question of the usage of language.

34:57.186 --> 34:58.968
Now, where does the difficulty arise?

35:00.970 --> 35:06.816
Well, it's almost amusing to read the commentators on this important verse.

35:09.499 --> 35:23.154
Large numbers of them immediately begin to say something like this, that the Apostle Paul here very clearly shows that he knew nothing at all about horticulture, that he was mainly a town's man.

35:23.714 --> 35:33.626
and that he does the most foolish thing, which preachers are given to doing, but which they should never do using an illustration when they don't know enough about the subject from which they're culling their illustration.

35:34.347 --> 35:43.158
They say, here is the apostle Paul telling us that the picture is the relationship of the gentle to the dew in the churches.

35:43.558 --> 35:53.010
It's exactly as if you take a bit of a wild olive tree, which is very poor in the matter of fruit production, and you graft it in to a good olive tree.

35:53.346 --> 35:59.856
Well, they say it's elementary, of course, any man who knows anything at all about horticulture knows that that is something that is just never done.

35:59.896 --> 36:04.243
What is done is the exact opposite.

36:04.263 --> 36:10.994
You always graft a good branch into one that isn't as good.

36:12.162 --> 36:17.110
And the result is he will then get a greater crop out of this grafted in branch.

36:17.391 --> 36:22.119
It makes use of the life and the sap that is in the other, but you never do it the other way around.

36:22.179 --> 36:29.731
They say this is quite elementary and it's merely indicative of the apostles' ignorance of this matter.

36:32.576 --> 36:37.143
Well, then you see they begin to do research work.

36:37.163 --> 36:38.706
And then they find

36:39.106 --> 36:42.210
that sometimes that is actually done after all.

36:43.231 --> 36:45.534
It doesn't come in practice.

36:45.554 --> 36:56.367
But certain scholars, William Ramsey in particular, was a great archaeologist and interested in these methods, he discovered that this was sometimes done.

36:57.969 --> 37:06.980
And if you had a good olive tree, which was becoming rather lethargic and lazy, it wasn't a bad thing to graft into that a bit of a wild olive tree.

37:07.440 --> 37:08.722
And this new graph

37:08.834 --> 37:17.848
provide a kind of stimulus to the old tree and wake it up again and make it produce better fruit and even produce fairly good fruit on the graft that you had grafted in.

37:19.110 --> 37:27.283
And so they feel that after all, you know, the Apostle Paul knew more about this business of horticulture than some of his critics tend to imagine and so on.

37:27.584 --> 37:29.166
And this is the great matter.

37:31.971 --> 37:36.498
Now all that seems to me to be completely and entirely irrelevant.

37:38.466 --> 37:45.194
And he chose the danger of going off a tangents because of some supposed special knowledge.

37:45.695 --> 37:49.499
Now I could easily elaborate on this point, people attending to do it today.

37:49.559 --> 37:56.728
I know people who say, now we understand things in the Bible we didn't before because of our recent knowledge.

37:56.748 --> 38:08.402
The moment you say that, you've already gone wrong because obviously the apostle uses illustrations which could be understood two thousand years ago.

38:08.802 --> 38:13.708
And if you can only understand an illustration in terms of modern scientific knowledge, you're wrong.

38:14.449 --> 38:18.635
That knowledge wasn't available then, so the apostle's illustration would have been of no value.

38:18.995 --> 38:25.263
But I say it is entirely of no value to us for this reason.

38:26.906 --> 38:36.498
That the apostle himself tells us in verse 24 that he is referring to something that is not according to nature.

38:37.410 --> 38:46.278
for if thou were cut out of the olive tree, which is wild by nature, and were graphed, uncrereta nature into a good olive tree.

38:47.580 --> 38:50.422
You see, this is a tremendous point here.

38:50.442 --> 38:55.787
The apostle says, God has done something that is unusual.

38:57.329 --> 39:00.271
God has done something that is miraculous.

39:01.933 --> 39:07.218
God has done something that enables even a wild olive tree to produce good olive.

39:08.226 --> 39:11.150
This is regeneration, if you like.

39:11.170 --> 39:14.373
God doesn't act according to nature in the matter of salvation.

39:15.895 --> 39:17.717
It takes a miracle to save a man.

39:18.038 --> 39:20.060
It takes a miracle to save the Gentiles.

39:20.401 --> 39:23.765
God does something contrary to nature, supernatural.

39:24.606 --> 39:31.474
He tells us that, so that we needn't waste any of our time in this recondite

39:31.938 --> 39:36.304
Archaeological discovery and try somewhere another to justify the Great Apostle.

39:36.324 --> 39:38.427
The Great Apostle tells us it's exactly what he's saying.

39:38.807 --> 39:40.350
He says this is the most amazing thing.

39:41.311 --> 39:45.136
Who would ever have imagined that there was any hope for the people like the Gentiles.

39:45.296 --> 39:55.610
But God, because he is God and because of the whole miraculous supernatural grace element, God is able to do this tremendous thing.

39:55.630 --> 40:01.138
And he says that is exactly and precisely what God has done.

40:02.242 --> 40:11.375
Well now then, it seems to me that we have given an exposition of the actual meaning of our terms.

40:13.017 --> 40:22.330
And I think it puts us into a position in which we will be able, next Friday night, God willing, to tackle this vital question.

40:23.412 --> 40:25.595
What is the olive tree?

40:26.817 --> 40:27.858
That's the whole key.

40:29.090 --> 40:41.987
Your exposition of the olive tree will decide exactly the view you take of the precise place of the Jews in the economy of God and in salvation.

40:42.487 --> 40:49.497
It will determine your view probably on certain events in connection with the second coming and the whole of the future.

40:49.817 --> 40:56.786
There is a teaching as you know which says that the Jews will always occupy a unique and special position.

40:57.378 --> 40:59.641
that the church will be divided into two sections.

40:59.701 --> 41:03.367
There will be a heavenly section and an earthly section and so on and so forth.

41:03.387 --> 41:05.610
All this is very relevant to that.

41:07.152 --> 41:17.807
And now having prepared the groundwork as it were, having looked at the terms and having seen in general what the apostle is saying, what he's saying is this.

41:18.128 --> 41:19.209
There is a knowledge tree.

41:20.511 --> 41:21.873
There were natural branches.

41:22.193 --> 41:23.696
They've been cut off and thrown away.

41:24.116 --> 41:25.458
Others have been put in.

41:26.242 --> 41:28.946
But still, natural branch is going to come in again.

41:28.986 --> 41:32.250
That's the main statement.

41:32.270 --> 41:33.152
Oh, exactly.

41:33.933 --> 41:35.755
Is this to be worked out in detail?

41:35.815 --> 41:41.223
What does he actually mean with respect to the Jews and the Gentiles?

41:41.283 --> 41:48.353
Well, as I say, God willing, I hope to look with you at this great statement about the olive tree.

41:49.555 --> 41:50.876
Next Friday evening.

41:51.297 --> 41:52.018
Let us pray.

41:55.234 --> 42:07.147
O Lord, our God, we come into thy holy presence once more, and we come marvelling more than ever at the mystery of thy grace and of thy way.

42:07.167 --> 42:18.359
O God, we thank thee for this root and fatness of which we thy people are partakers.

42:19.761 --> 42:24.466
We thank thee, O Lord, for the miracle of redeeming grace

42:24.546 --> 42:25.608
and of redemption.

42:26.629 --> 42:31.396
We thank thee for the miracle of the rebirth and of regeneration.

42:32.457 --> 42:51.225
We thank thee, O Lord, that because of this fitness of this blessed root, there is the possibility for all, O Lord, we pray thee to receive our praise and to increase our understanding of this glorious matter.

42:51.245 --> 42:52.146
And now,

42:52.450 --> 43:03.144
May the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ and the love of God, the fellowship in the communion of the Holy Spirit abide and continue with us now this night.

43:03.945 --> 43:13.778
Throughout the remainder of this hour, short and certain, earthly life and pilgrimage, and evermore, amen.

